AB  - We document that 20% of Compustat firms exhibit above-median investment rates despite having below-median marginal product of capital (MPK), seemingly “misallocating” resources. These firms are typically younger and more likely to experience substantial upwards jumps in sales and MPK in subsequent years. They contribute significantly to innovation, and their investments predict future aggregate productivity, creating value beyond their current MPK. We propose and estimate a simple endogenous firm growth model that captures key cross-sectional features and enables counterfactual analysis. Ignoring the potential for future jumps in hypothetical investment policies reduces MPK and investment dispersion but also lowers aggregate productivity.
